\begin_layout Standard
The main goal of our model is to see how consumer behaviour changes with
 respect to income differences 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\equiv y_{2}-y_{1}$
\end_inset

 .
 The fundamental assumption is that 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 are fixed in the short-term horizon considered for the consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We proceed by first discussing the trivial case when players (consumers)
 maximise accumulated assets in the terminal state.
 In this trivial case, any values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1,t\in[1,\tau]}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2,t\in[1,\tau]}$
\end_inset

 that keep the long-term expected value of assets the same for both players
 (consumers) provide the equilibrium conditions (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This seems aligned with the literature (e.g.
 St.
 Petersburg paradox) as well - where maximisation of terminal assets hardly
 represent consumer behaviour well.
 The Nash Equilibrium solution and the implications of income differences
 are discussed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Nash-Equilibrium"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main changes since the previous model are listed below
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
While the previous model didn't allow the time-horizons to change, the current
 model adopts a more general approach to time-horizons - letting assets
 reset at a general interval 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\tau$
\end_inset

 rather than at 
\begin_inset Formula $T=2$
\end_inset

.
 This allows more general considerations of consumer behaviour (including
 stochastic time-horizons).
 The assumptions pertaining to the short-term horizon considered by the
 consumers are detailed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:SinglePeriodMaximisation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unlike the previous model which relied on calamitous risk to accumulated
 assets, the current model banks upon consumption theory to interpret the
 long-term horizon only as the end-of-life for the consumer - where an additiona
l assumption is that the consumer is unable to transfer her accumulated
 assets to the progeny.
 In this no-bequest model, the consumer must therefore bank upon the game
 of social positions at the end of her life-cycle.
 The feature accommodates the objection made by dissimilarity between social
 and economic positions - since a significant number of players (consumers)
 may achieve a higher socio-economic position but fail to transfer their
 social status towards end-of-life (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details).
 A further clarification about how the schemes of promotion and demotion
 for two players in the game reflect the proportion of rich and poor is
 detailed in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:PopulationConstraint"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Unlike the previous model, a particular shape of utility function is not
 assumed for the consumer.
 Instead, the simplest case of maximising of assets under assumption of
 risk-neutral preferences is considered first.
 Utility functions with risk-aversion are to be introduced later along with
 relevant assumptions for consumer preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The promotion and demotion functions are assumed have a simper concave form
 and assists as a closed-form solution for a simple case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The martingale requirement for expected asset maximisation (simplest case)
 is specified and relevant assumptions are made for optimisation of total
 assets over the short-term horizon.
 The short-term consumer horizon for the consumer does not consider any
 efforts in the next period.
\end_layout

