\begin_layout Standard
The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 have been treated as exogenous so far.
 One condition that constraints the parameters is that of population of
 the poor and rich (i.e.
 the very claim of limits to social growth from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HarrodGrowth1958,scitovskyjoyless1992,HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 ).
 A relative difference between the poor and rich would always be maintained
 even though there is one poor or one rich person in the limiting case.
 The promotions are therefore balanced by demotions in the long-term.
 In any long-term equilibrium, the consumers moving from poor to the rich
 band would be balanced by those moving from rich to the poor band.
 Since, the two consumers are representative consumers, this does not need
 to be interpreted as consumer literally being promoted or demoted.
 Their proportions in population or the changing levels of separation between
 poor and rich could also amount to a demotion (see details in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ProportionsRichPoor"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 It is worth emphasising also that the promotion and demotions functions
 (
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

 respectively) do not represent distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 - but are binary distributions with a mean modified by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (see Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:lnu_concave"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The expectation of promotions is therefore defined for a particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 simply as 
\begin_inset Formula $W(\nu)(1)+(1-W(\nu))(0)$
\end_inset

 and similarly, the expected demotions are 
\begin_inset Formula $L(\nu)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

